<dl id="n53097x"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53097x">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53097x"> 97(x)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> frightfulness <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53097x"><li>FW 343.34 </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/lexmd.htm#n53097x">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/l39md.htm#n53097x">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53097x">MS BL 47480-81v</ms> </li><li>JJA 55:154 <a name="mdd5" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mdd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/md/mdd5.htm#n53097x">Draft: II.3&sect;4.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;Percy inaugurates new form of <mark>frightfulness</mark>,&rdquo; laughed the Major. &ldquo;May I be there when you catch your first!&rdquo; <p>The conversation dropped; other and more intimate topics anent the fair ones at home took its place; but in the mind of Percy FitzPercy the germ of invention was sown. When he went back to his battalion that night, in their so-called rest-billets, he was thinking. Which was always a perilous proceeding for Percy.</p> <small> H.C. McNeile (&ldquo;Sapper&rdquo;) <a name="SJW" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SJW"><cite title="source">John Walters</cite></a> (1927) The Man-Trap, 106</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: [Army slang] Frightfulness: this word was applied by English journalists to describe the real or imagined barbarity of the enemy Hun. </mm> </dd></dl>
